segments.text: November the 23rd, we're testing the tape, getting ready to chat with Mike House.
We're at his BMW dealership in Albuquerque.
Mike, add a sentence there.
Albuquerque, New Mexico, matter of fact.
Mike, as we begin, would you give a brief biographical summary
where you grew up and what your parents and so forth before getting to A&M.
Where was home?
I was born in 1951, July 1951.
At the time, my dad worked for American Airlines, and about every two years he would travel.
And dad and mom, as a matter of fact, I was to be...

born in Buffalo New York where dad was and dad wanted to make sure mom wanted to make sure I was a Texan so she flew home right about delivery time and lived with her mom and dad for about three weeks to make sure I was born in Texas and I was born in Ennis Texas which is where they are retired today and flew back to Buffalo and moved around a bit but ended up and grew up the majority of my life in Dallas and when I was a freshman in high school between freshman and sophomore moved to San Antonio
Graduated in San Antonio from Churchill High School.
And thought I wanted to go into oceanography.
And Texas A&M had a program that was top notch.
I thought I might be interested in also flying.
So the Air Force interested me and the ROTC program interested me.
And as a story in itself, I got in by the skin of my teeth by going through the junction program.
And that created some bonding that's gone on to this day.
Got into A&M in 69 and in four years was able to graduate with a business administration degree with a management major.
All right, so my next question is going to be, why did you attend A&M?
You attended A&M partly because of what you thought your major was going to be.
That is correct.
Had you been to visit before you came to enroll?
No, I had never been to the campus prior to three or four days before the freshman's
In those days, different than my kids now, I don't remember the choices.
And not that Dad wouldn't have given them to me if I would have asked for them.
This was my interest, and he did everything he could to help me go that direction.
But I didn't have a Newsweek book with 180 universities to choose from.
That just seemed like a logical choice.
So you went to Junction that first summer.
Correct.
Did you come to College Station and then go to Junction?
No, I went to Junction first.
I went to Junction and committed six weeks and about seven hours in college courses to see if I would be qualified academically.
And I guess I was just hoping I liked that email at this point.
Did your mom drive you, mom and dad drive you out to Junction?
I remember mom and dad, I had a little MG midget, and I remember my mom and dad followed me in that MG midget out to Junction and dropped me off.
I have not yet interviewed anyone about Junction.
So please describe that as fully as you can.
Oh, that's a great, it was a great program.

There were probably, if I were to pick a number, 40 or 50 of us, and we lived in a barrack kind of thing, and it had no windows, but it was screened, and bunk beds, and a common bath, and there were probably a half dozen upperclassmen that were there, and I guess they were taking courses as well, but they were predominantly there for supervision.
And I took biology and a lab.
And I took, seemed like it was an English course and got a PE credit.
So I came out with probably three or four credits through that science and another three credits for the English.
And I ended up with a strong B throughout.
So that got me in without a problem.
And of that group, there were probably 12 or so in my cabin or my barrack.
And probably...
Eight or nine of those made it to A&M, and I bet there wasn't of those 12, two or three of us eventually graduated.
Things happen.
I can remember that it's a summer camp feel and really heavy on physical.
I'm a runner, and I was a runner at the time.
I was the first guy I can remember at that semester to be able to run up to the cross, which was about a five mile up and five mile back.
And you go up at the top, there's this big cross at the top of the junction.
Then we got a group together, and we'd run it about every other day, because it got to be then at YDD Special.
It was just a fun time.
They had a big creek and river that went through there, and we had some swimming certification that we had to do.
And once everybody knew that they could swim, then it was a matter of pushing that program as far as we could.
We were in and out of the water all the time.
There were wild turkey.
I remember wild turkey roaming around all the time.
Deer.
And then I can remember the...

the uh the uh shaving cream fights and the restroom you know having a common bath with all those guys it was just you know running around in underwear and things that you just couldn't do normally and food was great and the atmosphere it was hot but you were never sweating you know and i'd probably go back to junction and i'd drip all the time but just something about i guess it's just your expectations and it just the whole thing was right and you'd go into town and the town was two streets
And you'd feel like you went into San Antonio, you know, because you've just been confined in this little deal.
But I had the opportunity about a year and a half ago, I made a special trip as I was going to San Antonio to go through Junction.
And to drive down that road and see, I think Texas Tech owns it now.
And it looked like it was some kind of a researcher or teacher development deal or something.
And it was a little, it was sad.
Not that it didn't look good, but it was sad not that it wasn't the way it was.
Do you remember who the teachers were in those two courses?
Absolutely not.
I couldn't help you one out.
I know we dissected frogs and animals and that kind of thing.
I just don't remember the details.
What, Louie Hauer in English or Bill Barzak?
Wasn't either of those.
Just too many years, I'll tell you.
Because I've never heard anything but positive about Junction, the Junction experience by the youngsters who were out there.
Describe a typical day.
What time did you get up?
It was an early morning day, but it was early morning like Sunday.
6.30 to 7, and no formation or anything.
And I think breakfast was, they almost required you to have breakfast.
I don't recall.
I just remember I always had breakfast.
I'm not a big breakfast eater.
And you would, it seemed like you'd do classes all morning, and then the afternoon would tend to fletch between some kind of academic and some kind of extracurricular activity.
All right, what about the biology lab?
Did you do that in the afternoon?
Ah.
Gosh, that was 1960.
30 years ago.
I would tend to say we did it in the morning.
It seemed like the morning was pretty much academic time.
And the afternoons, I can remember the afternoons were so hot that, again, we didn't sweat, but they were hot.
And I can remember you did have some nap time on your own, or you just had free time.
But you could take a nap, or you could go for a run, or you could go down to the river, or just do whatever you wanted to do.
It wasn't every hour regimented.
I guess if they were old enough then, that would be time that we would use as our own responsibility.
Now, you mentioned a little bit of playing around with shaving cream and things like that.
Were there any things that happened that now, in retrospect, that were in bad taste, too extreme?
No, no.
I would think, of what I recall, the things we did at A&M by choice were a notch more than we did at Junction.
Junction was kind of a coming out time, and I think we might have had a little reservation, a little less confidence in ourselves maybe than we did when we got to A&M.
But it was all a good humor, tame thing.
So you did six weeks there and then went home, then came back in the fall to A&M.
Right.
Did you come in that little MG?
I came in the MG, yeah.

You remember it took about, it had windows that were screwed in instead of rolled up, and it took about three weeks before one of my windows was taken, and it took about another three weeks before one of the tachometers was taken.
It just wasn't a good time to have a sports car in a place like Texas A&M.
I was definitely on the cutting edge of European cars.
And you were in the Corps.
right so that what what gear did you bring what kind of stuff but
I've been forewarned that they just don't allow a whole lot.
And I didn't bring much.
And I had kind of an unusual and unfortunate circumstance.
We came, I think, about a week early or five days early.
And about three days into that, my grandmother passed away unexpectedly.
And so I had to leave for a couple days for the funeral.
And when I came back, classes were in session.
And everybody, it was a little tough because the other freshmen had another two or three days to work on traditions.
how to do things, and I kind of had to pop in midstream, and people that didn't know me didn't give me that benefit of the doubt.
So it was a sink or swim for the first week there, but I caught on fire.
Describe your outfit and where you lived and so forth.
Hellcat 9, which is no longer there, and it was a tight group, but the seniors were, you didn't know the seniors, they were,
I don't know how it is today, but you just didn't allow the camaraderie with the older folks.
Juniors, you knew a little bit, like 20%.
Seniors, you might have known less than 5%.
Juniors, 20%, 25%.
And then the sophomores, you knew them 90%.
They were your face all the time.
And I can remember, I mean, there was hazing, but it's nothing that we didn't all involve in and enjoy.
But you wouldn't know.
You wouldn't go to the toilet.
You'd tend to use your sink if you could.
Just because you didn't want to get out and have to hit the wall and answer 12 questions and do another 73 push-ups.
I was class of 73, so that was the push-ups and set-ups I was doing all the time.
But I could rattle them off pretty good.
But you just didn't get out any more than you had to.
So you arrived in the fall of 60?
Fall of 69.
Describe a typical weekday
for you that freshman year?
What did it begin and what happened go through the whole day?
It seemed like they woke us up with a normal chime up and down the hall.
One of the freshmen would have to do his rhyme.
I can't remember the rhyme.
But they'd wake you up going up and down the hall and you'd have

15 or 20 minutes to get ready, and there was enough chaos that you probably didn't get hazed that 15 or 20 minutes because everybody was running to showers and using the toilet and that kind of thing, and you'd be on the wall, and you'd spend probably at least 5, no more than 10 minutes on the wall, and you'd have to be speaking Spanish all the way up and down.
And I was one of the few that bought Corfam shoes.
That's when Corfam came out.
And I was able to get, I bet I didn't know five people that got through their whole freshman year with Corfam shoes.
Because if the upperclassmen found out you did, oh, they would, we'd get thrown away.
But if you could save them, it sure saved a lot of shiny time.
And I had Corfam shoes, which helped me a lot.
I also didn't change my bed sheets the first, probably, well, until Christmas.
And I took them home Christmas holiday, and I had to throw them away.
What I would do is keep everything tucked very tight and slide in very gingerly.
and then slide out.
And I guess I wouldn't turn over at night, because I never screwed up my tuck.
But you would.
They didn't wash real well that semester.
But back in the day, you'd have your five or 10 minutes of up against the wall, and the sophomores quizzing you, and a few juniors walking down, just kind of giving you a hard time.
Then you'd go out in formation.
They would probably question you another five minutes, and then you'd have
the wake-up call and everything, and then you'd march to the, is it Sabisa Hall?
Were you at Northgate or Southgate?
Were you at Northside or the, or was it Duncan?
Duncan, Duncan, not Sabisa, Duncan.

Duncan, you'd go to Duncan, and you'd have, the meal would be, it would be difficult the first ten minutes, and then the upperclassmen would get to eat, and then you'd eat, and then you'd come back, and most of the upperclassmen were out of the way because they were already in the room.
You'd hustle in your room, hope you wouldn't get delayed,
get your books, get on the class.
And then the day was pretty tame.
I mean, you just kind of kept your nose clean.
It was fine.
And then at dinner time, you would have to go in formation again, same routine, march to dinner, and come back.
And I can remember that you had until 7.30 before you had to do your study.
And you would study from 7.30 to 10.00.
And then there were like 30 minutes of free time, but nobody left the rooms because they didn't want to get hazed, but you'd call or the phone would do whatever.
And then at 10.30, the lights out, unless you could get an upperclassman to allow you to maybe use a small minor's pipeline or something to continue studying.
If you had any free time in the afternoons, any unscheduled time, what did you do?

you know academically i had to work hard there were a lot of other ones that became easier to and i i used a lot of my afternoon studying where um usually i either use they had i don't know what they're called but they're small little retreats between the dorms this kind of common area and i would find a corner and everybody leave you alone to go pretty well or i would use the library

And if I use a library a lot, but if I had free time, I still like to run and I will run most every day and I will try to do that in the afternoon and get away from just get away from the dorms for an hour a day.
Was your freshman roommate a special person as you look back?
Did y'all have a Yeah, he remains one I'm in contact with.
He's a pilot for American Airlines.
I just had him for the first
And then in my sophomore year, I got a second roommate.
I had one or two roommates that I'm still close with.
At the very first of my freshman year, I settled in after about a month.
Had him all freshman year.
Remain close to him to this day.
And then I had a new roommate that graduated with me, and he's a pilot for Continental and Guam.
And he remained in the club.
Make believe that I had never heard about chow hall routine and food and so forth.
Describe A&M chow hall habits and food and so forth.
Well, I ate well because I didn't, I wasn't afraid of the system.
I enjoyed the system.
And I found ways to get around the system and to abuse the upperclassmen that pushed the system as much as I could get away with it.
So I would kind of put myself in the forefront.

And by doing that, that might have picked on you at first and quizzed you a lot the initial part of the meal because you had to stay at attention and you had to square your bites and you had to ask for food by the name, the alien name, and ask in a certain way.
And if you go ahead and jump into that and do it, they tend to leave you alone more than the guy that's kind of mild and meek and fat and calorie.
And by doing that, I ate well, and then they would leave, and I would eat even better.
And if there was an upperclassman that was giving me a hard time, I would find a way to use the system to help me get back to him.
And it's nothing of a total aggressive type of way, but it's just more of a competitive spirit that the Corps created at that time, and I assume still has today.
What were some of the food names, nicknames?
Spuds.
Bullneck was meat.
Cow was milk.
Bread.
Was that dill?
Still, that's exactly what it is.
I don't remember, but that's exactly what it was.
Did iced tea or coffee have a nickname?
If so, I don't recall.
See, I'm not a coffee drinker, so that's why I wouldn't have thought about it.
I don't remember when it happened.
What about things like green beans or mash?
Yeah, mash.
They had names.
They had names, but I just can't remember.
And I've heard that a few freshmen got in trouble at home at Thanksgiving when they slipped and asked for a certain food.
There were some, and I can't tell what they were, but there were some foods that had edgy names.
Yes.
And I did it.
I just know I did because everything else slipped out one time or the other.
You'd get around other people and it would just really be bad.
Were there any, I'll call it games, were there any games played by you and your fish buddies at the table?
Any things that y'all did maybe to get back at sophomores or other upperclassmen?
Yeah, and some I wouldn't repeat.
Oh, okay.
But it all kind of worked out, and I can remember putting gravy on the shoes, and they'd make you sit under the table if you did something wrong, and I'd have a pass food down, and I'd
take up the sides of your sole with mashed potatoes or something.
And they wouldn't catch it until later and not have any idea how it happened.
And I will tell you that we were able to put things in the food and whatnot just so that at least we'd feel better about buying it.
But to this day, they don't know.
So it all kind of worked out.
Let's see.
You mentioned the name of your outfit.
Do you hold that outfit closely in your heart?
Yeah, I do.
It's real tough, though.
You go back.
I've been back five or six times.
Since there isn't a squad of nine-year-olds, it kind of pulls at you.
You go back to the dorm that you were in and find your room.
As you went to class, did you and your friends have a routine about class, where to sit, what to carry to class, how to make contact with the instructor?
I don't remember that being anything that specific.
I remember getting the class, you would quickly learn what would be the least suggestive way to get to class.
And you would also, you'd have a way of walking by someone with them really wondering if you did see them.
Because if they did think you saw them and not speak, well, you would be in trouble.
But you knew half the guys you'd speak to would slow you down, so you didn't want to speak to them half the time.
So you'd find ways to dodge things and
Did you have any classes that freshman year that, as you look back, either the subject or the instructor was very important to you?
I got the feeling most of them were all way too big and just a little harder than they needed to be to the degree that I think they were really trying to lead us on.
And the professors had two to three hundred people, which was like chemistry, history, math was a little smaller than math was good, English was a reasonable size.
But I just felt like that AEM's criteria to get in was pretty easy in those days.
All right, but you were saying that the Junction helped you get in school.
How academically, how well did you do that first year?
I did fine.
I was probably in fine relative.
I mean, for me, I was just happy to be there and stay there.
I probably had a three, five, six, seven, something like that.
And I can remember of the, we had a map that somewhere in the city for 35 and 40 freshmen started.
And we had, I think the number was 13 of them graduated.
So, although that sounds like maybe a big number, it's too sad because I can think back to the other 25, 30 kids, and they were all great kids.
And just the circumstances were different in these places.
Please share, if you can, some jokes, pranks, good bull, that you and other freshmen pulled off.
I can remember having an opportunity to wake up in the morning and a junior or senior came to you and said he wanted you to be a fellow junior or senior.
you could do that in Puerto Rico and see who you are and everything else.
And they couldn't get back at you because, in fact, you were a messenger from someone else, but they didn't know who it was, which is a big mystery.
And I can remember, I can remember recording one guy with me, and he was one of the biggest, toughest guys in the world.
And me and a couple of guys came in at 2 a.m. and flipped on the lights.
And he was a scared person.
And it was just amazing to see a 252 or 275 pound guy that was three or four years older grabbing on the edge of his bed, just pleading me not to take him out of the room.
And we would, and we'd take him out.
But probably one of the better ones I can remember was the stripper guy who had a longer sack coming from one of the lights out front.
And we did it about 5, 5.30, and the formation was about
what retribution did he wreak on you perpetrators typically
There's just a limited amount they could do as far as quizzing you or making you do cooking.
You know, my freshman year, I was like 100, and I could do 1,000 servings.
So there's nothing they could do to really amuse me, and there's no question, lore-wise, traditionalizing that.
So there's just not a whole lot they could do.
They could sure try, but by Thanksgiving, you were so much in the system that you were going to make it.
Nothing bothered you.
And they could kind of tell, and there's really not a whole lot they could do.
Did your squadron commander's footlocker disappear?
He did, and we did.
We'd walk up and run the hall for a couple hours, and we had steam showers half a dozen times.
And we probably had a couple baths before that.

We probably had one or two baths, but I knew that it was, you know, it was also part of that business position deal that, you know, being a runner, I was always, this was back in the 60s when being in strength wasn't so big of a deal.
I enjoyed that kind of time.
And so, to me, I always look at that in myself as, well, I'll give myself a better shot at this.
All right, now, how did you all get the locker?
We had, at the time, we probably had about 30 guys there.
And we assigned responsibilities for each of the guys.
And we took a seat.
Our senior, he was a leader.
really sharp, polished kind of guy.
And so we took him out, and they did about two miles out of town.
They did give him a bath.
And they let him off about 2 a.m., just in the middle of the garden.
And he didn't get bathed until about 4 a.m. or 8 p.m.
So did you take the locker while he was out?
Yeah.
Where did y'all have the locker?
I wasn't in charge of that.
I don't remember that.
I was in charge.
I was one of the guys that got him and took him out to the car.
Did the footlocker reappear at Thanksgiving?
The footlocker did reappear at Thanksgiving.
But there was some definite time there.
That's right.
There was some pretty strong hazing going on in between.
until they did appear.
But we held them as long as we needed to hold them.
It wasn't like we cowered in front of them.
What about drownouts?
Were there any drownouts in your out that much?
Would a drownout be in the room?
Throwing water in the room, turning the sex on and leaving them on in that country?
Or dumping water on them while they were asleep?
We did some of that.
I can remember one guy we did that.
We spent all week doing that.
We filled up his room
How deep was it?
The whole room was full.
He opened the door, and it fell into the hall, and you couldn't see six inches in the room.
It was full of building paper.
We did a few duck walks, and we spent hours on that one, too.
Were you all then assigned to clean it up since you were freshmen?
No, he didn't know he did it.
And we really kept it quiet long enough to get it passed until a point where we really didn't have a problem with it.
That's how great it is.
All right.
What was it like to be a sophomore the next year?
It was heavy.
I didn't really get off on it.
I enjoyed my outfit.
I started enjoying some of the guys.
It was more better.
I can remember my freshman year, I couldn't have anything on my wall except for the bulletin board.
It had to be a bulletin board.
My sophomore year, they let me have a radio.
They let me have a small plug-in radio.
But you still couldn't have a stereo.
You couldn't have the outfits.
You could have
In the academics, look at the whole time you were there, who were, as you look back now, some important teachers, advisors, counselors,
that affected you?
He really enjoyed seeing me learn that he
I was too busy to look beyond and to think, well, if I get this guy, this grade, how am I going to get this?
Because he's a judge of every service.
And that kind of tainted my feeling to him that as a professor, he would explain it better than anyone.
And I had a professor prior to him that must have been my dad, must have had a program in my junior year.
And I had a fellow in my sophomore year, my freshman year,
Thank you.
When did you turn away from oceanography?
